 Turn to You / Por Siempre Tu: Music|publisher=[[Amazon.com]]|accessdate=September 16, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/I-Turn-To-You/dp/B00009KPHH/ref=tmm_vnl_title_0|title=I Turn to You [Vinyl]|publisher=Amazon.com|accessdate=2014-02-04}}</ref>\n|rowspan=\"2\"|June 13, 2000\n|[[Gramophone record|7\" single]]\n|{{N/A}}\n|-\n|[[CD single]]\n|{{N/A}}\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{All-4-One}}\n{{Christina Aguilera songs}}\n\n[[Category:1997 singles]]\n[[Category:2000 singles]]\n[[Category:1990s ballads]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Diane Warren]]\n[[Category:All-4-One songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written for films]]\n[[Category:Pop ballads]]\n[[Category:Christina Aguilera songs]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Joseph Kahn]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records singles]]\n[[Category:RCA Records singles]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Rudy P\u00e9rez]]\n[[Category:1996 songs]]\n[[Category:Contemporary R&B ballads]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1997 single by All-4-One}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = I Turn to You\n| cover      = All-4-One I Turn to You Single.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[All-4-One]]\n| album      = [[Space Jam: Music from and Inspired by the Motion Picture]]\n| released   = June 10, 1997\n| format     =\n| recorded   = September 1996\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Pop music|Pop]]|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]}}\n| length     = 4:52\n| label      = [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n| writer     = [[Diane Warren]]\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis|Jimmy Jam]]|[[Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis|Terry Lewis]]}}\n| prev_title = [[Someday (Disney song)|Someday]]\n| prev_year  = 1996\n| next_title = Love Shouldn't Hurt\n| next_year  = 1998\n}}\n\n\"'''I Turn to You'''\" is a song written by American songwriter [[Diane Warren]] and first recorded by R&B quartet [[All-4-One]] from the [[Space Jam (soundtrack)|soundtrack album]] to the film ''[[Space Jam]]'' (1996). The ballad, produced by [[Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis|Jimmy Jam]] and [[Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis|Terry Lewis]], received very little recognition until American pop singer-songwriter [[Christina Aguilera]] recorded it for her [[Christina Aguilera (album)|self-titled debut album]]. Aguilera, who worked with Warren in another song for her debut album, felt connected to the song after relating its lyrics to her relationship with her mother, and was encouraged by Warren to record the track.\n\nAguilera's version received mixed reviews from music critics, with some praising her vocal delivery, while others went on to criticize the ballad for being too clich\u00e9d. Nevertheless, the song became a huge success in the United States, peaking at number three on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and entered the charts of multiple countries across the world. In 2008, \"I Turn To You\" was covered by [[Nina Girado]], a [[Filipino people|Filipino]] [[Pinoy pop|pop]]/[[contemporary R&B|R&B]] singer, for her album ''[[Nina Sings the Hits of Diane Warren]]''.<ref name=amazon/> It was also used in many singing competition series, such as ''[[American Idol]]'' and most recently ''[[The Voice (U.S. TV series)|The Voice]]''.\n\n==Background==\nOn November 12, 1996, [[Atlantic Records]] released [[Space Jam (soundtrack)|the accompanying soundtrack]] for the film ''[[Space Jam]]''.<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/space-jam-mw0000080477|title=Space Jam Original Soundtrack|publisher=[[AllMusic]]. [[Rovi Corporation]]|accessdate=2014-02-05}}</ref> The soundtrack includes \"I Turn to You\", a song written by [[Diane Warren]] and recorded by boy band [[All-4-One]].<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/> Its production was done by [[James Harris III]] and [[Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis|Terry Lewis]].<ref>''[[Space Jam (soundtrack)|Space Jam]]'' liner notes. [[Atlantic Records]]. 1996.</ref> It is a [[pop music|pop]] song and lasts for a duration of 4:52 (four minutes and fifty-two seconds).<ref name=\"BillboardReview\">{{cite journal|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_KBAEAAAAMBAJ|page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_KBAEAAAAMBAJ/page/n72 73]|quote=billboard i turn to you space jam.|title=Reviews and Previews: Singles|date=1997-06-21|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]}}</ref> All-4-One member Delious Kennedy stated that after doing a music video, the group expected it to be a single, however the label decided against it, feeling that in spite of three hit singles, \"[[Fly Like an Eagle (song)#Seal version|Fly Like an Eagle]]\", \"[[I Believe I Can Fly]]\" and \"[[For You I Will (Monica song)|For You I Will]]\", the soundtrack had nothing else to offer. Warren, who felt the song had the potential to become a number one hit and even said to Atlantic that \"I'll put my own money behind it if you just release it,\"  decided to keep the song with the promise of getting someone else to record it and make it a hit single.<ref>{{cite journal |url= http://www.musictimes.com/articles/31713/20150316/all-4-one-talks-20th-anniversary-album-swear-success-being-longest-running-group-original-members-exlusive-interview.htm |title= All-4-One Talks 20th Anniversary Album, 'I Swear' Success & Being the Longest Running Groups With Original Members (EXCLUSIVE) |author= Mereb |journal= Music Times |date= March 16, 2015 |accessdate= 2017-02-05}}</ref>\n\n==Christina Aguilera version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = I Turn to You\n| cover      = Christina Aguilera - I Turn to You CD cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Christina Aguilera]]\n| album      = [[Christina Aguilera (album)|Christina Aguilera]]\n| B-side     = Por Siempre Tu\n| released   = March 30, 2000<ref name=billboardreview/>\n| format     = {{hlist|[[CD single|CD]]|[[Gramophone record|vinyl]]}}\n| recorded   = 1999\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Pop music|Pop]]|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]}}\n| length     = {{ubl|4:03 {{small|(radio edit)}}|4:33 {{small|(album version)}}}}\n| label      = [[RCA Records|RCA]]\n| writer     = [[Diane Warren]]\n| producer   = [[Guy Roche]]\n| prev_title = [[What a Girl Wants (Christina Aguilera song)|What a Girl Wants]]\n| prev_year  = 1999\n| next_title = [[Come On Over Baby (All I Want Is You)]]\n| next_year  = 2000\n| misc       = {{Audio sample\n | type        = single\n | file        = I Turn to You.ogg\n | description = \"I Turn to You\" by Christina Aguilera\n}}\n{{External music video|{{YouTube|z4q05resEvc}}}}\n}}\n\n=== Background ===\nAfter signing a record deal with [[RCA Records]], Christina Aguilera started working on songs from her debut album, set to be released in January 1999. [[Ron Fair]] was the album's [[executive producer]] and according to him, \"She was very much a raw talent, so building a collection of songs that would become her first album was a time-consuming process. We wanted to find the ones that could knock the door down and put her up there.\"<ref name=washingtonpost>{{cite news|last1=Harrington|first1=Richard|title=Christina Aguilera's Fast Track|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPcap/2000-02/13/003r-021300-idx.html|accessdate=June 26, 2014|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=February 13, 2000}}</ref> Famous songwriter [[Diane Warren]] was hired to write material for the album, eventually writing \"Somebody's Somebody\" and suggested that \"I Turn to You\" would be perfect for her voice.<ref>{{cite web|title=Diane Warren talks about \"I Turn to You\"|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gPGt7LBT8ZU&t=1m51s|website=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=June 29, 2014}}</ref> Eventually, Aguilera recorded \"I Turn to You\" and included it on her [[Christina Aguilera (album)|self-titled debut album]], and the song was chosen as the album's third single. It was sent to U.S. radio on March 30, 2000, while its CD single was released on June 13, 2000.<ref name=\"Amazon\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Turn-You-Por-Siempre-Tu/dp/B00004TWIX|title=I Turn to You/Por Siempre Tu [Single, Enhanced]|publisher=[[Amazon.com]]|accessdate=2014-02-04}}</ref> A Spanish version of the song entitled \"Por Siempre T\u00fa\" was recorded and also released as a single,<ref name=\"Amazon\"/> eventually being included on her first Spanish album, ''[[Mi Reflejo]]''.\n\n=== Composition ===\n\"I Turn to You\" is a [[ballad]] and lasts for a duration of 4:33 (four minutes and thirty-three seconds).<ref name=\"AMG\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/christina-aguilera-mw0000244313|title=Christina Aguilera &ndash; Christina Aguilera: Overview|publisher=AllMusic. Rovi Corporation|accessdate=2014-02-05}}</ref> According to the sheet music published by [[Alfred Publishing]], it has a slow [[tempo]] of 62 beats per minute and a key of [[D\u266d major]].<ref name=\"Sheet\">{{cite web|url=http://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtdFPE.asp?ppn=MN0052297&|title=I Turn to You Sheet Music|work=Musicnotes.com|publisher=[[Alfred Publishing]]|accessdate=2014-02-05}}</ref> Aguilera's vocal range spans from the low-note of [[A\u266d (musical note)|A\u266d<sub>3</sub>]] to the high-note of [[F (musical note)|F<sub>5</sub>]].<ref name=\"Sheet\"/> Besides being the songwriter, [[Diane Warren]] served as the [[executive producer]] of the track, while [[Guy Roche]] arranged, produced and programmed the track. Tim Pierce and Michael Thompson provided guitars, Mick Guzauski mixed it, while background vocals were provided by Aguilera and Sue Ann Carwell.<ref name=\"Notes\">{{cite AV media notes|others=Christina Aguilera|title=[[Christina Aguilera (album)|Christina Aguilera]]|year=1999|type= inlay cover|publisher= [[RCA Records]]|page=3}}</ref>\n\nLyrically, the song is about calling upon the love of that special one when times get tough.<ref name=\"pluggedin\">{{cite web|title=Christina Aguilera &#124; Christina Aguilera &#124; Plugged In |url=http://www.pluggedin.com/music/albums/1999/ChristinaAguilera-ChristinaAguilera.aspx |work=[[Plugged In]] |publisher=[[Focus on the Family]] |access-date=May 11, 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140513011759/http://www.pluggedin.com/music/albums/1999/ChristinaAguilera-ChristinaAguilera.aspx |archive-date=May 13, 2014 |df= }}</ref> For Aguilera, the song \"is about that sort of perfect love, which we all dream. This kind of song can make you feel safe and warm anytime of the year. And there's no one better to turn to for that than my own mother,\" she claimed.<ref>{{cite web|title=Christina Aguilera I Turn to You Live|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uxN6q2pSv54|website=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=June 29, 2014}}</ref> \"For a shield, from the storm for a friend, for a love to keep me safe and warm, I turn to you/For the strength to be strong, for the will to carry on/For everything you do, for everything that's true, I turn to you,\" she sings in the chorus.<ref name=metrolyrics>{{cite web|title=Christina Aguilera - I Turn To You Lyrics|url=http://www.metrolyrics.com/i-turn-to-you-lyrics-christina-aguilera.html|website=[[MetroLyrics]]|accessdate=June 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Critical reception ===\n\"I Turn to You\" received mixed reviews from [[music critics]], with some praising Aguilera's vocals, while others criticizing the ballad for being too formulaic. In a positive review, Amanda Murray of ''[[Sputnikmusic]]'' called the song a \"truly well-made pop song\", writing that \"the music plays a diminished role and Aguilera's voice is allowed to soar and shine moreso than on any of the other tracks.\"<ref name=sput>{{cite news|last1=Murray|first1=Amanda|title=Review: Christina Aguilera Christina Aguilera - Sputnikmusic|url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/5110/Christina-Aguilera-Christina-Aguilera/|accessdate=June 27, 2014|work=[[Sputnikmusic]]|date=February 2, 2006}}</ref> Despite writing that Aguilera \"does deliver on the glorious mid-section,\" Chuck Taylor of ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' felt that the track \"is about as clich\u00e9d as ballad gets,\" sounding \"more like a leftover from the stack rather than the kind of glorious anthem Warren is capable of,\" calling it a remake of [[Whitney Houston]]'s \"[[Count On Me (Whitney Houston and CeCe Winans song)|Count On Me]]\".<ref name=billboardreview>{{cite book|title=Billboard Magazine: April 1, 2000 Issue|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ww4EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA23&dq=christina+aguilera+i+turn+to+you+review&hl=pt-BR&sa=X&ei=HuqtU8i6HfHMsQSg24GACw&ved=0CB0Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=christina%20aguilera%20i%20turn%20to%20you%20review&f=false|website=[[Google Books]]|publisher=[[Billboard Magazine]]|accessdate=June 27, 2014}}</ref>\n\nNikki Tranter of ''[[PopMatters]]'' called it \"a nice little song ruined by that horrid pop beat threatening to destroy cheesy love songs for all time,\" writing that \"the beat alone drags Christina's [[Etta James]] potential back down to [[Mariah Carey]] quality.\"<ref name=popmatters>{{cite news|last1=Tranter|first1=Nikki|title=Christina Aguilera: self-titled &#124; PopMatters|url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/aguilerachristina-st/|accessdate=June 29, 2014|work=[[PopMatters]]|date=August 23, 1999}}</ref> Beth Johnson of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' called it a \"maudlin ballad best suited to thirtysomething divas,\" calling it \"a near-identical rip-off of Diane Warren's own [[Celine Dion]] smash, '[[Because You Loved Me]]'.\"<ref name=\"EW\">{{cite magazine| url = http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,272813,00.html| title = Christina's World| first = Johnson| last = Beth| magazine = [[Entertainment Weekly]]| date = August 20, 1999| accessdate = 2008-07-30}}</ref> Julene Snyder of ''[[Sonic.net]]'' considered \"I Turn to You\" a \"tear-jerker designed to incite concertgoers to link arms and sing along, even while some of us cringe at the over-the-top vocal histrionics.\"<ref name=sonic.net>{{cite news|last1=Snyder |first1=Julene |title=Teen Genie |url=http://www.sonicnet.com/artists/ai_album.jhtml?id=517128&ai_id=509026 |access-date=June 26, 2014 |work=[[Sonic.net]] |date=September 10, 1999 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010702010123/http://www.sonicnet.com/artists/ai_album.jhtml?id=517128&ai_id=509026 |archive-date=July 2, 2001 }}</ref> ''[[AOL Radio]]'' ranked the song at number 8 on her \"Top 10 Hits\".<ref name=aolradio>{{cite web|last1=Adwoa Ofori|first1=Nana|title=Top 10 Christina Aguilera Songs|url=http://www.aolradioblog.com/2010/06/06/top-christina-aguilera-songs/|website=[[AOL Radio]]|accessdate=June 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Chart performance ===\n\"I Turn to You\" debuted at number 50 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart, becoming the Hot Shot Debut of the week ending April 15, 2000. It also debuted on the Hot 100 Airplay chart, at number 47, with an audience of 28.5 million, also becoming the highest-debuting song on the airplay chart.<ref name=billboarddebut>{{cite news|last1=Pietroluongo|first1=Steve|title=Hot 100 Spotlight|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4w4EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA109&dq=christina+aguilera+i+turn+to+you+billboard&hl=pt-BR&sa=X&ei=KqWvU_KfD9PNsQSjxoHwDw&ved=0CCkQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=christina%20aguilera%20i%20turn%20to%20you%20billboard&f=false|accessdate=June 29, 2014|work=[[Billboard Magazine]]|publisher=[[Google Books]]|date=April 15, 2000}}</ref> In its second week, the song jumped to number 39,<ref>{{cite news|title=The Billboard Hot 100: April 22, 2000|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8A4EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA78&dq=christina+aguilera+i+turn+to+you+billboard&hl=pt-BR&sa=X&ei=bIGwU-WYLJS-sQSx9YLwDQ&ved=0CB0Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=i%20turn%20to%20you&f=false|accessdate=June 29, 2014|work=[[Billboard Magazine]]|publisher=[[Google Books]]|date=April 22, 2000}}</ref> while in its third week the song climbed to number 30.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Billboard Hot 100: April 29, 2000|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EA8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA93&dq=christina+aguilera+i+turn+to+you+billboard&hl=pt-BR&sa=X&ei=bIGwU-WYLJS-sQSx9YLwDQ&ved=0CCMQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=i%20turn%20to%20you%20&f=false|accessdate=June 29, 2014|work=[[Billboard Magazine]]|publisher=[[Google Books]]|date=April 29, 2000}}</ref> The song entered the top-twenty on the week of May 20, 2000 (at number 19),<ref>{{cite news|title=The Billboard Hot 100: April 29, 2000|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PA8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA109&dq=christina+aguilera+i+turn+to+you+billboard&hl=pt-BR&sa=X&ei=3YKwU5KpI7K0sQT5-4CwBw&ved=0CB0Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%20i%20turn%20to%20you&f=false|work=[[Billboard Magazine]]|publisher=[[Google Books]]|date=May 20, 2000}}</ref> and peaked on the week ending July 1, 2000, with a huge climb from number 17 to number 3, becoming its peak position and Aguilera's third top-ten single.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Billboard Hot 100: July 1, 2000|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-g8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA109&dq=christina+aguilera+i+turn+to+you+Billboard+Sales+Chart&hl=pt-BR&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiZ8rfHwL7KAhUDEZAKHTnpBH0Q6AEILTAB#v=onepage&q=christina%20aguilera%20i%20turn%20to%20you%20Billboard%20Sales%20Chart&f=false|work=[[Billboard Magazine]]|publisher=[[Google Books]]|date=July 1, 2000}}</ref> The single peaked at number one on the Hot 100 Singles Sales chart on July 15, 2000.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Billboard Hot 100 Singles Sales: July 15, 2000|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BxAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA69&dq=christina+aguilera+i+turn+to+you+billboard&hl=pt-BR&sa=X&ei=3YKwU5KpI7K0sQT5-4CwBw&ved=0CCkQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=christina%20aguilera%20i%20turn%20to%20you%20billboard&f=false|work=[[Billboard Magazine]]|publisher=[[Google Books]]|date=July 15, 2000}}</ref> It peaked at number 5 on the [[Adult Contemporary]] chart, becoming her highest charting single at the time.<ref name=adult/> In [[Canada]], the song peaked inside the top-ten, at number 10.<ref name=canada>{{cite web|title=Christina Aguilera - Chart History &#124; AllMusic|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/christina-aguilera-mw0000244313/awards|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=June 27, 2014}}</ref>\n\n\"I Turn to You\" reached the top-twenty in [[New Zealand]], [[Spain]] and the [[United Kingdom]]. In New Zealand, \"I Turn to You\" peaked at number 11 and spent 18 weeks on the chart; her longest of the album,<ref name=nz/> in [[Spain]], it peaked at number 12,<ref name=spain/> while in the United Kingdom, the song peaked at number 19, becoming Aguilera's lowest charting single there.<ref name=uk/> Elsewhere, the song cracked the top-forty. In [[Australia]], \"I Turn to You\" also became Aguilera's lowest single on the charts, reaching number 40 and spending 4 weeks on the chart.<ref name=aria/>\n\n===Music video===\n[[File:Iturntoyouvideo.png|thumb|right|200px|Christina Aguilera singing on a [[Computer-generated imagery|CGI]] rooftop in the music video.]]\nThe music video for \"I Turn to You\" was shot from February 26 to February 28, 2000<ref name=makingthevideo>{{cite web|title=Christina Aguilera MTV Making The Video I Turn To You Part 1|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gPGt7LBT8ZU&t=2m29s|website=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=June 29, 2014}}</ref> and it was directed by [[Joseph Kahn]].<ref name=imdb/> Mistakenly, in the show ''[[Making the Video]]'', the director says Rupert C. Almont. According to Aguilera, \"This video is a little different than my other videos [...] I'm pretty much on a stage just belting my heart out. And the whole city that I'm singing out to, and I'm narrating different events that are going on in this city are in-sync with me.\"<ref name=makingthevideo/> Production was finished on March 26, 2000,<ref>{{cite web|title=Christina Aguilera MTV Making The Video I Turn To You Part 2|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nJ6URBTLEYQ|website=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=June 29, 2014}}</ref> and it premiered on April 3, 2000, during the [[MTV]]'s ''Making the Video''<ref name=imdb>{{cite web|title=Making the Video: Christina Aguilera: I Turn to You|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0640131/|website=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=June 29, 2014}}</ref> and made it world premiere on [[MTV]]'s ''[[Total Request Live]]'' on April 10, 2000.<ref>{{cite web|title=The TRL Archive - Recap: April 2000|url=http://atrl.net/trlarchive/?s=recap&y=2000&m=04|website=ATRL.Net|accessdate=June 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe video's storyline follows a young woman getting into an accident, after arguing with her mother. Later, her mother is seen worriedly waiting for word on where she is at the late hour. The video ends with the girl being given the support she needs by her mother. Christina is seen singing in front of a microphone before walking in the rain with an umbrella, and on a rooftop.<ref name=celebritycafe>{{cite news|last1=Learned|first1=Elizabeth|title=Top 10 Christina Aguilera Music Videos|url=http://thecelebritycafe.com/feature/2014/02/top-10-christina-aguilera-music-videos?page=7|accessdate=June 27, 2014|work=The Celebrity Cafe|date=February 21, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140912081135/http://thecelebritycafe.com/feature/2014/02/top-10-christina-aguilera-music-videos?page=7|archive-date=September 12, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> The rooftop scene was shot in front of a [[green screen]], not in a real rooftop, as seen on the making of. ''The Celebrity Cafe'' listed it at number 5 on their \"Top 10 Christina Aguilera music videos\" list.<ref name=celebritycafe/>\n\n=== Live performances ===\nAguilera performed \"I Turn to You\" in a number of places, first being in 1999 alongside ''[[Tevin Campbell]]'' at the ''[[Alma Awards]]'' (April 11, 1999) followed ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' (April 8, 2000)<ref>{{cite web|title=Saturday Night Live: Season 25, Episode 16 Christopher Walken/Christina Aguilera|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0694774/|website=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=June 29, 2014}}</ref> & [[Rosie O'Donnell Show]] being the first three.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Rosie O'Donnell Show Episode dated 11 April 2000|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0694774/|website=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=June 29, 2014}}</ref> She also performed on a medley with \"[[What a Girl Wants (Christina Aguilera song)|What a Girl Wants]]\" during the [[American Music Awards of 2000]], \"Party In The Park\",<ref>{{cite web|title=Christina Aguilera - I Turn To You (Party In The Park LONDON 2000)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EVYos2IiXOE|website=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=June 29, 2014}}</ref> \"The Music Factory Dutch\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Christina Aguilera - I Turn To You The Music Factory Dutch 2000|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7EOkwC6Jj30|website=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=June 29, 2014}}</ref> and many others. Aguilera also performed the track during her \"[[Christina Aguilera in Concert]]\" tour as well as on the \"[[Genie Gets Her Wish|Genie Gets Her Wish Home Video]]\", where Heather Phares of ''[[AllMusic]]'' praised the performance of the song, writing that on the track \"Aguilera's undeniable vocal gifts shine through,\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Genie Gets Her Wish - AllMusic|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/genie-gets-her-wish-mw0000255570|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=June 29, 2014}}</ref> and on her \"[[My Reflection|My Reflection DVD]]\" (2001).<ref>{{cite web|title=My Reflection - DVD - Saraiva|url=http://www.livrariasaraiva.com.br/produto/850651/my-reflection-dvd/|website=Saraiva.com.br|accessdate=June 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Spanish version ===\n{{Infobox song\n| name     = Por Siempre Tu\n| cover    =\n| alt      =\n| type     =\n| artist   = Christina Aguilera\n| album    = [[Mi Reflejo]]\n| released =\n| format   =\n| recorded = 2000\n| studio   =\n| venue    =\n| genre    =\n| length   = {{Duration|m=4|s=05}}\n| label    = RCA\n| writer   = {{hlist|[[Rudy P\u00e9rez]]|Diane Warren}}\n| producer = {{hlist|Rudy P\u00e9rez|Guy Roche|[[Ron Fair]] {{small|(executive producer)}}|Diane Warren {{small|(executive producer)}}}}\n}}\n\nIn 1999, Aguilera began recording her first Spanish album in Miami with Cuban-American producer [[Rudy P\u00e9rez]].<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dwgEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA51&dq=intitle:billboard+aguilera+spanish&hl=en&sa=X&ei=4zuNUuPhNeXwyAG_toC4Dg&ved=0CDMQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Aguilera En Espa\u00f1ol|author=John Lannert|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=October 23, 1999|accessdate=November 20, 2013|volume=111|issue=43|page=51}}</ref> He composed Spanish versions of five songs from Aguilera's debut album, including \"I Turn to You\", which became \"Por Siempre Tu\".<ref name=\"mireflejonotes\">Liner notes of ''[[Mi Reflejo]]'' (2001). Christina Aguilera. RCA Records.</ref> \"Por Siempre Tu\" was written and produced by P\u00e9rez among the former producer of the song, [[Guy Roche]]. [[Diane Warren]] and [[Ron Fair]] executively produced the track, while Aguilera, P\u00e9rez and Wendy Pendersen provided background vocals.<ref name=\"mireflejonotes\"/> P\u00e9rez stated that Aguilera did not know any Spanish while recording; he remedied the problem by phonetically writing out lyrics and included a system that allowed Aguilera to pronounce the \"r's\" in the songs.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ehEEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA17&dq=christina+aguilera+mi+reflejo+600,000&hl=en-419&sa=X&ei=kvD9ULitFor-8AS5q4CIAg&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=christina%20aguilera%20mi%20reflejo%20600%2C000&f=false|title=Rudy Perez Tops Hot Latin Tracks Producers Lists for 2000|last=Cobo|first=Leila|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=December 30, 2000|accessdate=January 21, 2013|volume=112|issue=53|page=17}}</ref>\n\nHer decision to record in Spanish scored points with the Spanish-speaking audience, said Haz Montana, program director at the [[Los Angeles]] Latin-music station KSSE-FM. \"There's usually a sizeable rejection when someone just translates an English song and doesn't speak a lick of Spanish,\" he said. \"She's defied the odds.\" He further commented: \"Her accent is impeccable,\" he said. \"There may be a slight nuance here and there that tells you that Spanish is not her first language, but that's as far as it gets.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Vanhorn|first1=Teri|title=With Three Albums In Works, Christina Aguilera Eyes Long Career|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/820070/with-three-albums-in-works-christina-aguilera-eyes-long-career/|accessdate=June 28, 2014|work=[[MTV News]]|date=March 24, 2000}}</ref> \"Por Siempre Tu\" was released as a single during the time \"I Turn to You\" was also released.<ref name=discogsporsiempretu>{{cite web|title=Christina Aguilera \u2013 Por Siempre T\u00fa (CD) at Discogs|url=http://www.discogs.com/Christina-Aguilera-Por-Siempre-T%C3%BA/release/5361107|website=[[Discogs]]|accessdate=June 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\nSean Piccoli of [[Sun-Sentinel]] described Diane Warren's song as, \"one of those [[Wind Beneath My Wings]] lifter-uppers that she cranks out for the likes of [[Celine Dion]] and [[Faith Hill]],\" and noted that \"Aguilera, like Warren's other interpreters, is faithfully cringe-inducing and overdramatic. She shares their deafness to understatement and can no more reel it in for this or any other moment that might benefit from a lighter touch.\" Piccoli's thoughts on the ''Mi Reflejo'' album were summed up as, \"For anyone who thinks Taco Bell is authentic Mexican, this is Latin pop.\"<ref name=\"Piccoli\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2000-09-25/lifestyle/0009221060_1_mi-reflejo-latin-pop-por-siempre-tu|title=Only Aguilera's Words Are Spanish|last=Piccoli|first=Sean|work=[[Sun-Sentinel]]|publisher=Tribune Company|date=September 25, 2000|accessdate=April 30, 2013}}</ref> \"Por Siempre Tu\" peaked at number six on the [[Hot Latin Songs|''Billboard'' Hot Latin Songs]] chart, becoming Aguilera's first top-ten single on the Latin charts.<ref name=\"latinsongs\">{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=christina aguilera|chart=Latin Songs C}}|title=Christina Aguilera - Chart history: Latin Songs|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|accessdate=May 1, 2013}}</ref> It spent 10 weeks on the charts.<ref name=\"latinsongs\"/>\n\nA music video for the song was directed by [[Joseph Kahn]], who also directed the video for \"I Turn to You\". The scenes were the same as the English version, while also featuring Christina singing the Spanish version in front of a microphone and on a rooftop.<ref>{{cite web|title=Christina Aguilera - Por Siempre T\u00fa|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Eh83bxcvvts&list=UUlx2ih2Nx8enGmsMsA6C3BQ&index=9&feature=plcp|website=CAguileraVEVO|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=June 29, 2014}}</ref> Aguilera performed the Spanish version on the \"Caracas Pop Festival\" in 2001 as well as on her [[Christina Aguilera in Concert|Mi Reflejo Tour]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Christina Aguilera Por Siempre Tu Caracas Pop Festival 2001|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bSb4J4fwedk|website=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=June 29, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Por Siempre T\u00fa & I Turn To You - Panama Mi Reflejo Tour|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=c6xOy78EbxM|website=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=June 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Track listings===\n;US CD single<ref name=\"UCD\"/>\n#\"I Turn to You\" \u2013 4:01\n#\"Por Siempre T\u00fa\" \u2013 3:53\n\n;Europe maxi single<ref name=\"SwiCharts\"/>\n#\"I Turn To You (Radio Edit)\" \u2013 3:53\n#\"I Turn To You (Radio Edit - Music Intro)\" \u2013 4:03\n#\"What A Girl Wants (Thunderpuss Fiesta Edit)\" \u2013 3:25\n#\"What A Girl Wants (Thunderpuss Dirty Radio Mix)\" \u2013 3:16\n\n===Personnel===\n* [[Christina Aguilera]] - lead and background vocals\n* [[Guy Roche]] - producer, arranger, keyboards, programming\n* [[Michael Landau]], [[Michael Thompson (guitarist)|Michael Thompson]] - electric guitars\n* [[Tim Pierce]] - acoustic guitar\n* John Glaser - [[Moog synthesizer]]\n* Sue Ann Carwell - background vocals\n\n=== Other versions and impact ===\nCCM singer [[Jonathan Pierce]] covered the song for his 1999 album ''Sanctuary''.\n\n\"I Turn to You\" was part of the soundtrack of Brazilian soap opera ''[[Uga-Uga]]'' (2000).<ref name=ugaugasoundtrack>{{cite web|title=Uga Uga Internacional [Brazil] - AllMusic|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/i-turn-to-you-mt0000088318|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=June 29, 2014}}</ref> In 2005, American singer [[Vonzell Solomon]] performed the track during the [[American Idol (season 4)|fourth season]] of ''[[American Idol]]''. In 2008, [[Nina Girado]], a [[Filipino people|Filipino]] [[Pinoy pop|pop]]/[[contemporary R&B|R&B]] singer, covered the track for her fourth studio album ''[[Nina Sings the Hits of Diane Warren]]''.<ref name=amazon>{{cite web|title=Amaozn.com: Sings the Hits of Diane Warren|url=https://www.amazon.com/Sings-Hits-Diane-Warren-Nina/dp/B001F3EGL0|website=[[Amazon.com]]|accessdate=October 31, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2013 interview, American recording artist [[Lady Gaga]] stated that she was inspired by Aguilera's version of the track, saying, \"When I was 15, I was singing 'I Turn to You' at the top of my lungs trying to hit all her notes. So she was an inspiration to me to have a wider vocal range.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Lady Gaga Calls Christina Aguilera Feud \"Total Nonsense\" on Watch What Happens Live|url=http://www.wetpaint.com/the-voice/articles/2013-09-12-lady-gaga-christina-aguilera-beef|accessdate=June 28, 2014|work=[[Wetpaint]]}}</ref> Most recently, the song was used as a battle song between contestants Beth Spangler and Mia Pfirrman during the [[The Voice (U.S. season 7)|seventh season]] of the American singing competition ''[[The Voice (U.S. TV series)|The Voice]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Beth Spangler and Mia Pfirrman sing 'I Turn to You' on 'The Voice.'|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-beth-spangler-mia-pfirrman-the-voice-20141022-embeddedvideo.html|accessdate=October 31, 2014|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=October 22, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Charts===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n====Weekly charts====\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (2000)\n!scope=\"col\"|Peak<br/>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Australia|40|refname=aria|artist=Christina Aguilera|song=I Turn to You|accessdate=February 4, 2014|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|30|artist=Christina Aguilera|song=I Turn to You|accessdate=February 4, 2014|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|30|artist=Christina Aguilera|song=I Turn to You|accessdate=February 4, 2014|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Wallonia|33|artist=Christina Aguilera|song=I Turn to You|accessdate=February 4, 2014|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadatopsingles|7|chartid=7289|accessdate=February 4, 2014|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Croatia ([[Croatian Radiotelevision|HRT]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hrt.hr/hr/top20/lista.html|title=HR Top 20 Lista|publisher=[[Croatian Radiotelevision]]|access-date=April 5, 2019|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20000610000204/http://www.hrt.hr/hr/top20/lista.html|archive-date=June 10, 2000}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|4\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany|65|artist=Aguilera,Christina|song=I Turn to You|accessdate=February 4, 2014|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Ireland2|17|song=I Turn to You|rowheader=true|accessdate=June 1, 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch40|40|year=2000|week=26|accessdate=February 4, 2014|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|50|artist=Christina Aguilera|song=I Turn to You|accessdate=June 1, 2018|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|11|refname=nz|artist=Christina Aguilera|song=I Turn to You|accessdate=February 4, 2014|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Scotland|22|date=20000722|accessdate=June 21, 2018|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Spain|12|refname=spain|artist=Christina Aguilera|song=I Turn to You|accessdate=February 4, 2014|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n