{"title_page": "Proper orbital elements", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=December 2008}}\n[[File:proper osculating element difference.png|thumb|Distribution of the difference between proper and osculating orbital elements for [[asteroid]]s with semi-major axes lying between 2 and 4&nbsp;[[Astronomical unit|AU]].]]\n[[File:Asteroid osculating vs proper elements.png|right|thumb|350px|proper (right) and osculating (left) orbital elements for [[asteroid]]s in the [[asteroid belt]]. Note how [[asteroid family]] clumps are not discernible on the left.]]\nThe '''proper orbital elements''' of an orbit are constants of motion of an object in space that remain practically unchanged over an astronomically long timescale. The term is usually used to describe the three quantities:\n*''proper semimajor axis'' (''a<sub>p</sub>''),\n*''proper eccentricity'' (''e<sub>p</sub>''), and\n*''proper inclination'' (''i<sub>p</sub>'').\n\nThe '''proper elements''' can be contrasted with the [[osculating orbit|osculating]] Keplerian [[orbital elements]] observed at a particular time or [[epoch (astronomy)|epoch]], such as the [[semi-major axis]], [[Orbital eccentricity|eccentricity]], and [[inclination]]. Those osculating elements change in a [[quasi-periodic motion|quasi-periodic]] and (in principle) predictable manner due to such effects as perturbations from planets or other bodies, and precession (e.g. [[perihelion precession]]). In the [[Solar System]], such changes usually occur on timescales of thousands of years, while proper elements are meant to be practically constant over at least tens of millions of years.\n\nFor most bodies, the osculating elements are relatively close to the proper elements because precession and perturbation effects are relatively small (see diagram). For over 99% of [[asteroid]]s in the [[asteroid belt]], the differences are less than 0.02&nbsp;AU (for [[semi-major axis]] ''a''), 0.1 (for [[Eccentricity (orbit)|eccentricity]] ''e''), and 2\u00b0 (for [[inclination]] ''i'').\n\nNevertheless, this difference is non-negligible for any purposes where precision is of importance. As an example, the asteroid [[Ceres (dwarf planet)|Ceres]] has osculating orbital elements (at [[epoch (astronomy)|epoch]] November 26, 2005)\n{| align=\"center\" style=\"border:1px solid #CCC; margin-left:15px;\" cellpadding=\"5\"\n! ''[[Semimajor axis|a]]'' !! ''[[eccentricity (orbit)|e]]'' !! ''[[inclination|i]]''\n|-\n| 2.765515&nbsp;[[Astronomical unit|AU]] || 0.080015 || 10.5868\u00b0\n|}\nwhile its proper orbital elements (independent of epoch) are<ref name=Ceres-POE>{{cite web\n  |title=AstDyS-2 Ceres Synthetic Proper Orbital Elements\n  |publisher=Department of Mathematics, University of Pisa, Italy\n  |url=https://newton.spacedys.com/astdys/index.php?pc=1.1.6&n=1\n  |accessdate=2011-09-19}}</ref>\n{| align=\"center\" style=\"border:1px solid #CCC; margin-left:15px;\" cellpadding=\"5\"\n! ''[[Semimajor axis|a<sub>p</sub>]]'' !! ''[[Orbital eccentricity|e<sub>p</sub>]]'' !! ''[[inclination|i<sub>p</sub>]]''\n|-\n| 2.767096&nbsp;AU || 0.116198 || 9.6474\u00b0\n|}\nA notable exception to this small-difference rule are [[asteroid]]s lying in the [[Kirkwood gap]]s, which are in strong orbital resonance with Jupiter.\n\nTo obtain proper elements for an object, one usually conducts a detailed simulation of its motion over timespans of several millions of years. Such a simulation must take into account many details of celestial mechanics including perturbations by the planets. Subsequently, one extracts quantities from the simulation which remain unchanged over this long timespan; for example, the mean inclination, eccentricity, and semi-major axis. These are the proper orbital elements.\n\nHistorically, various approximate analytic calculations were made, starting with those of [[Kiyotsugu Hirayama]] in the early 20th century. Later analytic methods often included thousands of perturbing corrections for each particular object. Presently, the method of choice is to use a computer to numerically integrate the equations of [[celestial dynamics]], and extract constants of motion directly from a numerical analysis of the predicted positions.\n\nAt present the most prominent use of proper orbital elements is in the study of [[asteroid family|asteroid families]], following in the footsteps of the pioneering work of Hirayama. A [[Mars-crosser asteroid]] [[132 Aethra]] is the lowest numbered asteroid to not have any proper orbital elements.\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Hirayama family]]\n* [[Perturbation (astronomy)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*Z. Kne\u017eevi\u0107 et al., ''The Determination of Asteroid Proper Elements'', pp.&nbsp;603\u2013612 in Asteroids III, University of Arizona Press (2002).\n*[http://saj.matf.bg.ac.rs/195/pdf/001-008.pdf Z. Kne\u017eevi\u0107: COMPUTATION OF ASTEROID PROPER ELEMENTS: RECENT ADVANCES, Serbian Astronomical Journal, vol. 195, pp.&nbsp;1-8 (2017).]\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://newton.spacedys.com/astdys/index.php?pc=5 Latest calculations of proper elements for numbered minor planets at astDys].\n*[http://asteroids.matf.bg.ac.rs/fam/properelements.php Asteroid proper orbital elements dataset at Asteroid Families Portal]\n\n[[Category:Orbits]]\n", "text_old": "{{Citations missing|date=December 2008}}\n[[File:proper osculating element difference.png|thumb|Distribution of the difference between proper and osculating orbital elements for [[asteroid]]s with semi-major axes lying between 2 and 4 [[Astronomical unit|AU]].]]\n[[File:Asteroid osculating vs proper elements.png|right|thumb|350px|proper (right) and osculating (left) orbital elements for [[asteroid]]s in the [[asteroid belt]]. Note how [[asteroid family]] clumps are not discernible on the left.]]\nThe '''proper orbital elements''' of an orbit are constants of motion of an object in space that remain practically unchanged over an astronomically long timescale. The term is usually used to describe the three quantities:\n*''proper semimajor axis'' (''a<sub>p</sub>''),\n*''proper eccentricity'' (''e<sub>p</sub>''), and\n*''proper inclination'' (''i<sub>p</sub>'').\n\nThe '''proper elements''' can be contrasted with the [[osculating orbit|osculating]] Keplerian [[orbital elements]] observed at a particular time or [[epoch (astronomy)|epoch]], such as the [[semi-major axis]], [[Orbital eccentricity|eccentricity]], and [[inclination]]. Those osculating elements change in a [[quasi-periodic motion|quasi-periodic]] and (in principle) predictable manner due to such effects as perturbations from planets or other bodies, and precession (e.g. [[perihelion precession]]). In the [[Solar System]], such changes usually occur on timescales of thousands of years, while proper elements are meant to be practically constant over at least tens of millions of years.\n\nFor most bodies, the osculating elements are relatively close to the proper elements because precession and perturbation effects are relatively small (see diagram). For over 99% of [[asteroid]]s in the [[asteroid belt]], the differences are less than 0.02 AU (for [[semi-major axis]] ''a''), 0.1 (for [[Eccentricity (orbit)|eccentricity]] ''e''), and 2\u00b0 (for [[inclination]] ''i'').\n\nNevertheless, this difference is non-negligible for any purposes where precision is of importance. As an example, the asteroid [[Ceres (dwarf planet)|Ceres]] has osculating orbital elements (at [[epoch (astronomy)|epoch]] November 26, 2005)\n{| align=\"center\" style=\"border:1px solid #CCC; margin-left:15px;\" cellpadding=\"5\"\n! ''[[Semimajor axis|a]]'' !! ''[[eccentricity (orbit)|e]]'' !! ''[[inclination|i]]''\n|-\n| 2.765515 [[Astronomical unit|AU]] || 0.080015 || 10.5868\u00b0\n|}\nwhile its proper orbital elements (independent of epoch) are<ref name=Ceres-POE>{{cite web\n  |title=AstDyS-2 Ceres Synthetic Proper Orbital Elements\n  |publisher=Department of Mathematics, University of Pisa, Italy\n  |url=http://hamilton.dm.unipi.it/astdys/index.php?pc=1.1.6&n=1\n  |accessdate=2011-09-19}}</ref>\n{| align=\"center\" style=\"border:1px solid #CCC; margin-left:15px;\" cellpadding=\"5\"\n! ''[[Semimajor axis|a<sub>p</sub>]]'' !! ''[[Orbital eccentricity|e<sub>p</sub>]]'' !! ''[[inclination|i<sub>p</sub>]]''\n|-\n| 2.767096 AU || 0.116198 || 9.6474\u00b0\n|}\nA notable exception to this small-difference rule are [[asteroid]]s lying in the [[Kirkwood gap]]s, which are in strong orbital resonance with Jupiter.\n\nTo obtain proper elements for an object, one usually conducts a detailed simulation of its motion over timespans of several millions of years. Such a simulation must take into account many details of celestial mechanics including perturbations by the planets. Subsequently, one extracts quantities from the simulation which remain unchanged over this long timespan; for example, the mean inclination, eccentricity, and semi-major axis. These are the proper orbital elements.\n\nHistorically, various approximate analytic calculations were made, starting with those of [[Kiyotsugu Hirayama]] in the early 20th century. Later analytic methods often included thousands of perturbing corrections for each particular object. Presently, the method of choice is to use a computer to numerically integrate the equations of [[celestial dynamics]], and extract constants of motion directly from a numerical analysis of the predicted positions.\n\nAt present the most prominent use of proper orbital elements is in the study of [[asteroid family|asteroid families]], following in the footsteps of the pioneering work of Hirayama. A [[Mars-crosser asteroid]] [[132 Aethra]] is the lowest numbered asteroid to not have any proper orbital elements.\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Hirayama family]]\n* [[Perturbation (astronomy)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*Z. Kne\u017eevi\u0107 et al., ''The Determination of Asteroid Proper Elements'', p. 603-612 in Asteroids III, University of Arizona Press (2002).\n\n*[http://saj.matf.bg.ac.rs/195/pdf/001-008.pdf Z. Kne\u017eevi\u0107: COMPUTATION OF ASTEROID PROPER ELEMENTS: RECENT ADVANCES, Serbian Astronomical Journal, vol. 195, pp. 1-8 (2017).]\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://hamilton.dm.unipi.it/astdys/index.php?pc=5 Latest calculations of proper elements for numbered minor planets at astDys].\n\n*[http://asteroids.matf.bg.ac.rs/fam/properelements.php Asteroid proper orbital elements dataset at Asteroid Families Portal]\n\n[[Category:Orbits]]\n", "name_user": "AlanM1", "label": "safe", "comment": "MOS:UNITSYMBOLS, NEODyS link fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proper_orbital_elements"}
{"title_page": "Alois Brunner", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n|name= Alois Brunner\n|image= Alois Brunner.JPG\n|caption= Brunner in 1940\n|birth_date= {{birth date|1912|4|8|df=y}}\n|death_date= {{death year and age|2001|1912}}\n|birth_place= [[Rohrbrunn|N\u00e1dk\u00fat]], [[Kingdom of Hungary]], [[Austria-Hungary]] \n|death_place= [[Damascus]], [[Syria]]\n|placeofburial= Al-Affif cemetery, Damascus, Syria (likely)\n|allegiance={{flag|Nazi Germany}}\n|branch=[[File:Schutzstaffel Abzeichen.svg|20px]] [[Schutzstaffel]]\n|serviceyears=1932\u20131945\n|rank= [[Hauptsturmf\u00fchrer]] (head storm leader)\n|battles  = [[World War II]]\n|commands= [[Drancy internment camp]]\n|laterwork= Advisor to the [[Syria]]n government; arms dealer in [[Egypt]]\n}}\n\n'''Alois Brunner''' (8 April 1912 \u2013 2001<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/nazi-war-criminal-alois-brunner-died-syria-basement-061723415.html|title=Nazi war criminal Brunner 'died in Syria basement in 2001'|website=Yahoo!|access-date=24 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"timesofisrael\"/>) was an Austrian ''[[Schutzstaffel]]'' (SS) officer who worked as [[Adolf Eichmann]]'s assistant. Brunner is held responsible for sending over 100,000 [[European Jews]] to ghettos and concentration camps in eastern Europe. He was commander of the [[Drancy internment camp]] outside Paris from June 1943 to August 1944, from which nearly 24,000 people were deported.\n\nAfter some narrow escapes from the [[Allies of World War II|Allies]] in the immediate aftermath of [[World War II]], Brunner fled West Germany in 1954, first for Egypt, then Syria, where he remained until his death. He was the object of many manhunts and investigations over the years by different groups, including the [[Simon Wiesenthal Center]], the [[Serge and Beate Klarsfeld|Klarsfelds]] and others. He was condemned to death ''[[trial in absentia|in absentia]]'' in France in 1954 for [[crimes against humanity]]. He lost an eye and then the fingers of his left hand as a result of [[letter bomb]]s sent to him in 1961 and 1980, reportedly by Israeli [[Secret service|intelligence]].<ref name=\"Bergman\" /> The government of Syria under [[Hafez el-Assad]] came close to [[extradition|extraditing]] him to [[East Germany]] before this plan was halted by the [[fall of the Berlin Wall]] in November 1989. Brunner survived all the attempts to detain him and was unrepentant about his activities to the end. During his long residence in Syria, Brunner was reportedly granted [[Right of asylum|asylum]], a generous salary and protection by the ruling [[Ba'ath Party]] in exchange for his advice on effective [[torture]] and [[interrogation technique]]s used by the Germans in [[World War II]].<ref>Adam Chandler, [https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2014/12/eichmanns-best-man-lived-and-died-in-syria/383296 \"Eichmann's Best Man Lived and Died in Syria\"], ''The Atlantic Magazine'', 1 December 2014.</ref>\n\nStarting in the 1990s and continuing for two decades, there was periodic media speculation about Brunner's exact whereabouts and his possible demise. In November 2014, the [[Simon Wiesenthal Center]] reported that Brunner had died in Syria in 2010,<ref name=swc2014/> and that he was buried somewhere in Damascus. The exact date of death and place of death are unknown, with recent information pointing to 2001 as the year of his death.\n\n==Second World War==\nBorn in [[Rohrbrunn|N\u00e1dk\u00fat]], [[Vas County (former)|Vas, Austria-Hungary]] (now Rohrbrunn, [[Burgenland]], Austria), he was the son of Joseph Brunner and Ann Kruise. He joined the [[Nazi Party]] in 1931 and the ''[[Sturmabteilung]]'' (SA) in 1932. After joining the SS in 1938, he was assigned to the staff of the [[Central Office for Jewish Emigration]] in Austria and became its director in 1939. He worked closely with [[Adolf Eichmann]] on the [[Nisko Plan]], a failed attempt to set up a Jewish reservation in [[Nisko|Nisko, Poland]], later that same year.{{sfn|Cesarani|2005|p=128}}\n\nBrunner held the rank of SS-''[[Hauptsturmf\u00fchrer]]'' (captain) when he organized deportations to [[Nazi concentration camps]] from [[Vichy France]] and [[Slovak Republic (1939-1945)|Slovakia]]. He was commander of a train of Jews deported from [[Vienna]] to [[Riga]] in February 1942. En route, Brunner shot and killed Jewish financier Siegmund Bosel, who, although ill, had been hauled out of a Vienna hospital and placed on the train. According to historian Gertrude Schneider, who as a young girl was deported to Riga on the same train, but survived the Holocaust:{{quote|Alois Brunner chained Bosel, still in his pajamas, to the platform of the first car\u2014our car\u2014and berated him for having been a profiteer. The old man repeatedly asked for mercy; he was very ill, and it was bitterly cold. Finally Brunner wearied of the game and shot him. Afterward, he walked into the car and asked whether anyone had heard anything. After being assured that no one had, he seemed satisfied and left.<ref>Schneider, Gertrude, ''Journey Into Terror: The Story of the Riga Ghetto'', p. 25, Westport, Connecticut, USA, Praeger, 2001; {{ISBN|0-275-97050-7}}</ref>}}\n\nBefore being named commander of [[Drancy internment camp]] near Paris in June 1943, Brunner deported 43,000 Jews from [[Vienna]] and 46,000 from [[Salonika]].<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite news|title=French court strikes blow against fugitive Nazi|url=https://www.theguardian.com/nazis/article/0,2763,445717,00.html|publisher=The Guardian|date=3 March 2003|accessdate=30 July 2007|location=London, UK|first=Jon|last=Henley}}</ref> He was personally sent by Eichmann in 1944 to [[Slovak Republic (1939-1945)|Slovakia]] to oversee the deportation of Jews. In the last days of the [[Third Reich]], he managed to deport another 13,500 from Slovakia<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> to [[Theresienstadt]], [[Sachsenhausen concentration camp|Sachsenhausen]], [[Bergen-Belsen concentration camp|Bergen-Belsen]], and [[Stutthof]] of whom a few survived; the remainder, including all the children, were sent to Auschwitz, where none are known to have survived.<ref name=\"Porter-2009\">{{cite book|last=Porter|first=Anna|authorlink=Anna Porter|title=Kasztner's Train: The True Story of an Unknown Hero of the Holocaust|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pfY4gV1B6moC&pg=PA246|accessdate=11 January 2016|date=26 May 2009|publisher=Walker Publishing|location=New York|isbn=978-0-8027-1596-8|page=[https://archive.org/details/kasztnerstrain00anna/page/246 246]|chapter=23. The End of Summer|origyear=2007|oclc=236340976|quote=In mid-October, Captain Alois Brunner began to empty the Sered camp of its almost twenty thousand Slovak Jews, even as the Slovak insurrection was defeated by four German SS divisions. Some of those who were sent to Theresienstadt survived the war. A few survived at the Sachsenhausen camp in Germany, Stutthof in Poland, and Bergen-Belsen. The rest, including all the children, were murdered in Auschwitz. Brunner had always taken great pleasure in the murder of children.|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/kasztnerstrain00anna/page/246}}</ref> According to some accounts, Brunner was responsible for the deportation of 129,000 people to death camps.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=FELSTINER|first=MARY|title=Commandant of Drancy: Alois Brunner and the Jews of France|date=1987|journal=Holocaust and Genocide Studies|volume=2|issue=1|pages=21\u201347|doi=10.1093/hgs/2.1.21|issn=8756-6583}}</ref>\n\nWhile serving as the commandant at Drancy, Brunner was remembered for his exceptional brutality. He personally conducted interrogations of new prisoners, and survivors of the camp have claimed that his office was covered in bloodstains and bullet holes. He instituted torture even for slight offences. As he was personally responsible to Eichmann, he circumvented the typical chain of command that included [[Helmut Knochen]], the Chief of the SS in Paris, and [[Heinz R\u00f6thke|Heinz Rothke]], the Jewish Affairs expert of the German police. He introduced a rigid system of categorization to control the inmates using information about their race and ethnicity derived from the interrogations. He deliberately misled prisoners about the living standards of their destinations at the extermination camps in the [[General Government]], including [[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz-Birkenau]]. Brunner also led round-ups of Jews in the [[Italian occupation of France|Italian Military Administration of France]] when the Germans assumed control in 1943 following the [[Armistice of Cassibile]], ended all legal exemptions preventing Jews from being deported by Vichy France, and extended the deportations to Jews of French nationality. He continued deportations and arrests even as the [[Allies of World War II|Allies]] and the [[Free France|Free French Forces]] advanced towards Paris.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Postwar flight and escape to Syria==\nIn an 1985 interview with the West German magazine ''[[Bunte]]'', Brunner described how he escaped capture by the Allies immediately after World War II. The identity of Brunner was apparently mixed up with that of another SS member with the same surname, Anton Brunner, who was executed for war crimes. Alois, like [[Josef Mengele]], did not have the [[SS blood group tattoo|SS blood type tattoo]], which prevented his identity from detection in an Allied prison camp. Anton Brunner, who had worked in [[Vienna]] deporting Jews, was confused after the war with Alois due to the shared surname, including by historians such as [[Gerald Reitlinger]].<ref>Schneider, Gertrude, ''Journey into terror: story of the Riga Ghetto'' (2nd abbr. edition), Westport, Connecticut, Praeger, 2001, pp. 54, 167; {{ISBN|0-275-97050-7}}</ref>\n\nClaiming he had \"received official documents under a false name from American authorities\", Brunner claimed he had found work as a driver for the [[United States Army]] in the period after the war.<ref>{{cite news|title=In Syria, a Long-Hunted Nazi Talks|newspaper=The New York Times|date=29 October 1985|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/10/29/world/in-syria-a-long-hunted-nazi-talks.html|first=James M.|last=Markham}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Nazi Criminal Says Mixup Aided His Escape|newspaper=The New York Times|date=7 November 1985|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/11/07/world/around-the-world-nazi-criminal-says-mixup-aided-his-escape.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=George J. Annas|title=Mengele's Birthmark: The Nuremberg Code in United States Courts|year=1991|journal=The Journal of Contemporary Health Law and Policy|volume=7|pages=17\u201346|pmid=11645690}}</ref>\n\nIt has been alleged that Brunner found a working relationship after World War II with the ''[[Gehlen Organization]]''.<ref>{{cite book|author=Peter Wyden|title=The Hitler Virus: The Insidious Legacy of Adolf Hitler|year=2001|publisher=Arcade Publishing}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first1=Georg|last1=Hafner|first2=Esther|last2=Schapira|title=Die Akte Alois Brunner|language=de|year=2000|publisher=Campus Verlag}}</ref><ref name=\"Ibtimes.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/alois-brunner-nazi-war-criminal-who-found-home-syria-725811|title=Alois Brunner: The Nazi War Criminal Who Found a Home in Syria|publisher=Ibtimes.com|date=18 July 2012|accessdate=4 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe fled [[West Germany]] only in 1954, on a fake [[Red Cross]] passport, first to Rome, then [[Republic of Egypt (1953\u20131958)|Egypt]], where he worked as a weapons dealer, and then to [[Syrian Republic (1946\u201363)|Syria]], where he took the [[pseudonym]] of Dr. Georg Fischer. In Syria, he was hired as a government adviser. The exact nature of his work is unknown. Syria had long refused entry to French investigators as well as to [[Nazi hunter]] [[Serge Klarsfeld]], who spent nearly 15 years bringing the case to court in France. [[Simon Wiesenthal]] tried unsuccessfully to trace Brunner's whereabouts. However, [[communism|communist]] [[East Germany]], led by [[Erich Honecker]], negotiated with Syria in the late 1980s to have Brunner [[extradition|extradited]] and arrested in Berlin.<ref name=\"halted-extradition\">{{cite web|url=http://www.expatica.com/de/news/german-news/fall-of-berlin-wall-halted-extradition-of-key-nazi-report_166452.html|title=Fall of Berlin Wall halted extradition of key Nazi: report|publisher=Expatica.com|accessdate=9 November 2012|date=2009-10-24}}</ref> The government of Syria under [[Hafez el-Assad]] was close to extraditing Brunner to East Germany, but the [[fall of the Berlin Wall]] in November 1989 severed contacts between the two regimes and halted the extradition plan.<ref name=\"halted-extradition\"/>\n \t\nIn the ''[[Bunte]]'' interview, Brunner was quoted as saying he regrets nothing and that all of the Jews deserved their fate. According to a widely quoted 1987 telephone interview with the ''[[Chicago Sun Times]]'', he was reported to have said: \"All of [the Jews] deserved to die because they were the Devil's agents and human garbage. I have no regrets and would do it again.\"<ref name=\"US State Dept document\">{{cite web|last1=US Department of State|title=Nazi War Criminal Alois Brunner's Presence in Damascus Hits the Papers Again|url=http://nsarchive.gwu.edu/NSAEBB/NSAEBB150/box14_di_file/doc04.pdf|website=The National Security Archive|accessdate=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nUntil the early 1990s, he lived in an apartment building on 7 Rue Haddad in Damascus, meeting with foreigners and occasionally being photographed.<ref name=\"guardian2001\">{{cite news|author=Jon Henley in Paris|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2001/mar/03/warcrimes.germany|title=French court strikes blow against fugitive Nazi|publisher=The Guardian|date=3 March 2001|accessdate=4 March 2014|location=London, UK}}</ref> In the 1990s, the French Embassy received reports that Brunner was meeting regularly and having tea with former East German nationals.<ref>{{cite web|author=Georges Malbrunot|date=21 July 2011|url=http://blog.lefigaro.fr/malbrunot/2011/07/alois-brunner-les-allemands-on.html|title=Alo\u00efs Brunner: les Allemands ont d\u00e9truit les notes de renseignements|publisher=Blog.lefigaro.fr|accessdate=4 March 2014}}</ref> According to ''[[The Guardian]]'', he was last seen alive by reliable witnesses in 1992.<ref name=\"guardian2001\"/>\n\nIn December 1999, unconfirmed reports surfaced that Brunner had died in 1996 and been buried in a Damascus cemetery. However, he was reportedly sighted at the Meridian Hotel in [[Damascus]] by German journalists that same year, where he was said to be living under police protection.<ref>{{cite news|author=Jo Glanville|url=https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/1999/nov/28/featuresreview.review|title=He's the last Nazi criminal still at large. But where is he?|publisher=Guardian|date=28 November 1999|accessdate=4 March 2014|location=London, UK}}</ref> The last reported sighting of him was at the Meridian Hotel in late 2001 by German journalists.<ref name=\"Ibtimes.com\"/>\n\nIn 2011, ''[[Der Spiegel]]'' reported that the German intelligence service [[Bundesnachrichtendienst]] had destroyed its file on Brunner in the 1990s, and that remarks in remaining files contain conflicting statements as to whether Brunner had worked for the BND at some point.<ref>{{cite news|title=BND vernichtete Akten zu SS-Verbrecher Brunner|language=de|publisher=[[Der Spiegel]]|date=20 July 2001}}</ref>\n\n==Assassination attempts==\nIn 1961 and 1980, letter bombs were sent to Brunner while he was a resident in Syria. As a result of the letter bomb he received in 1961, he lost an eye, and in 1980, he lost the fingers on his left hand when the parcel blew up in his hands. The senders of the letter bombs were not known.<ref>[http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,960365,00.html \"The Nazi of Damascus\"], ''Time Magazine'', 11 November 1985.</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">''{{lang|fr|Alois Brunner \u2013 La haine irr\u00e9ductible}}'', by Didier Epelbaum, preface by [[Serge Klarsfeld]], published by Calmann-L\u00e9vy, January 1990.</ref>\n\nA 2018 article in ''[[Newsweek]]'' by journalist [[Ronen Bergman]] disclosed that the 1961 bomb was sent by Military Intelligence Unit 188, a branch of the [[Israel Defense Forces]] and was the first target of a new method of [[letter bomb]] that was developed for deployment against ex-Nazi scientists working for [[Gamal Abdel Nasser]] in developing missiles targeting Israel. The article, excerpted from Bergman's book ''[[Rise and Kill First]]'', says that Brunner was located by Israeli spy [[Eli Cohen]].<ref name=\"Bergman\">{{cite news|last1=Bergman|first1=Ronen|authorlink1=Ronen Bergman|title=Israel's secret war against Hitler's scientists|url=http://www.newsweek.com/2018/04/20/israel-secret-war-mossad-hitler-scientists-world-war-ii-egypt-nasser-883630.html|accessdate=25 May 2018|work=Newsweek|date=12 April 2018|language=en}}</ref> According to information released by the Israeli intelligence agency [[Mossad]], it was behind the 1980 bomb.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/.premium-the-mossads-botched-assassination-attempts-on-nazi-war-criminals-1.5449633 | title=Not Just Mengele the Mossad's Botched Assassination Attempts on Nazi War Criminals| newspaper=Haaretz| date=2017-09-11| last1=Aderet| first1=Ofer}}</ref>\n\n==Convictions in absentia==\nGermany and other countries unsuccessfully requested his extradition. He was twice sentenced to death ''[[trial in absentia|in absentia]]'' in the 1950s; one of those convictions was in France in 1954. In August 1987, an [[Interpol]] \"[[red notice]]\" was issued for him. In 1995, German state prosecutors in [[Cologne]] and [[Frankfurt]] posted a $330,000 reward for information leading to his arrest.<ref name=\"McKale\">Donald M. McKale, {{cite book|title=Nazis after Hitler: How Perpetrators of the Holocaust Cheated Justice and Truth|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers|year=2011|isbn=978-1442213180|page=290|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=paOLRR7q15wC&lpg=PP1&pg=PP1}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 March 2001, he was found guilty ''in absentia'' by a French court for [[crimes against humanity]],<ref name=\"about\">Bridget Johnson,[http://worldnews.about.com/od/crime/tp/nazimostwanted.htm \"Most Wanted Nazis\"], About.com; accessed 27 December 2016.</ref> including the arrest and deportation of 345 orphans from the [[Paris]] region (which had not been judged in the earlier trials) and was sentenced to [[life imprisonment]]. According to [[Serge Klarsfeld]], the trial was largely symbolic\u2014an effort to honour the memories of victims. Klarsfeld's own father, arrested in 1943, was reportedly one of Brunner's victims.<ref name=\"Guardian2001\">[https://www.theguardian.com/nazis/article/0,2763,445717,00.html \"French court strikes blow against fugitive Nazi\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 3 March 2001.</ref>\n\n==Later attempts to locate==\nIn 2003, British newspaper ''[[The Guardian]]'' described him as \"the world's highest-ranking Nazi fugitive believed still alive.\" Brunner was last reported to be living in 2001 in [[Syria]], whose government had long rebuffed international efforts to locate or apprehend him, but was presumed dead {{as of|2012|lc=y}}.<ref name=euronews>{{cite news|title=Who are the most wanted Nazis?|url=http://www.euronews.com/2012/07/16/who-are-the-most-wanted-nazis|accessdate=24 July 2014|work=Euronews|date=16 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, for an episode titled \"Hunting Nazis\", the television series ''[[Unsolved History]]'' used [[facial recognition software]] to compare Alois Brunner's official SS photograph with a recent photo of \"Georg Fischer\", and came up with a match of 8.1 points out of 10, which they claimed was, despite the elapse of over 50 years in aging, equivalent to a match with 95% certainty. [[Brazilians|Brazilian]] police were reportedly investigating whether a suspect living in the country under an assumed name is actually Alois Brunner. Deputy Commander Asher Ben-Artzi, the head of Israel's [[Interpol]] and Foreign Liaison Section, passed on a Brazilian request for Brunner's [[fingerprint]]s to Nazi hunter [[Efraim Zuroff]], head of the [[Simon Wiesenthal Center]] in [[Jerusalem]], but Zuroff could not find any.<ref>[http://www.jpost.com/Jewish-World/Jewish-News/Intl-hunt-on-for-top-Nazi-fugitive \"Int'l hunt on for top Nazi fugitive\"], ''[[The Jerusalem Post]]'', 28 December 2005.</ref>\n\nIn July 2007, the Austrian Justice Ministry declared that they would pay \u20ac50,000 for information leading to his arrest and extradition to Austria.<ref>[http://www.justiz.gv.at/_cms_upload/_docs/auslobung_englisch.pdf Warrant of Apprehension], ''Austrian Justice Ministry''; accessed 27 December 2016.{{in lang|de}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2009, the Simon Wiesenthal Center acknowledged the \"slim\" possibility of Brunner still being alive.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/in_depth/7857753.stm|title=The hunt for the last Nazis|date=23 March 2009|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref> In 2011, some media reports still insisted he could be alive.<ref>{{cite news|first=Ben|last=Forer|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/worlds-wanted-left-list/story?id=13693016|title=World's Most Wanted: Who's Left on the List?|work=[[ABC News]]|date=26 May 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.20min.ch/news/dossier/denhaag/story/Die-meistgesuchten-Kriegsverbrecher-24050426|title=Die meistgesuchten Kriegsverbrecher|work=20 Minuten|date=26 May 2011|accessdate=10 June 2011|language=German}}</ref>\n\nBrunner was removed from the Simon Wiesenthal Center's [[List of most-wanted Nazi war criminals]] in 2014.<ref name=swc2014/>\n\n==Death==\nOn 30 November 2014, the [[Simon Wiesenthal Center]] reported receiving credible information that Brunner had died in [[Syria]] in 2001. He would have been 97 or 98 years old. Partly due to the ongoing [[Syrian Civil War]], the exact date and place of death are unknown.<ref name=swc2014>{{cite book|publisher=[[Simon Wiesenthal Center]]|location=Los Angeles, California|title=2014 Annual Report on the Status of Nazi War Criminals|url=http://www.wiesenthal.com/atf/cf/%7B54d385e6-f1b9-4e9f-8e94-890c3e6dd277%7D/WIESENTHAL-CENTER_2014-ANNUAL-NAZI-WAR-CRIMNAL-REPORT-V.2.PDF|year=2014|access-date=2014-06-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181030024822/http://www.wiesenthal.com/atf/cf/%7B54d385e6-f1b9-4e9f-8e94-890c3e6dd277%7D/WIESENTHAL-CENTER_2014-ANNUAL-NAZI-WAR-CRIMNAL-REPORT-V.2.PDF|archive-date=2018-10-30|url-status = dead|df=}}</ref><ref name=\"time.com\">\"A Notorious Nazi War Criminal Died in Syria Four Years Ago\", time.com, 2 December 2014.</ref>\n\nAccording to the director of the Wiesenthal Center, Dr. [[Efraim Zuroff]], the information came from a \"reliable\" former German [[secret service]] agent who had served in the Middle East. The information also was reported in the press. The new evidence revealed that Brunner was buried in an unknown location in Damascus around 2010, unrepentant of his crimes to the end. Zuroff said that, owing to the civil war in Syria, the exact location of Brunner's grave is impossible to know.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-30275358|title=Nazi war criminal Alois Brunner 'died in Syria'|work=BBC|date=1 December 2014|accessdate=27 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, a French magazine ''{{ill|XXI (magazine)|lt=XXI|fr|XXI}}'' interviewed one of Brunner's guards in Syria as he was locked up in a squalid Damascus basement at the end of the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.revue21.fr/tous_les_numeros#n-37_le-nazi-de-damas|title=Le nazi de Damas|website=Revue XXI|language=French|date=11 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-38586945|title=Nazi war criminal Alois Brunner 'died in Syria squalor'|website=BBC|date=11 January 2017}}</ref> The guard said that Brunner \"suffered and cried a lot in his final years, everyone heard him\", \"couldn\u2019t even wash\" and had to eat \"an egg or a potato\". He also added that Brunner died in December 2001 and was buried at Al-Affif cemetery in Damascus.<ref name=\"timesofisrael\">{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/nazi-war-criminal-alois-brunner-died-in-syria-basement-in-2001-report/|title=Nazi war criminal Alois Brunner died in Syria basement in 2001 \u2013 report|website=The Times of Israel|date=11 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of people who disappeared mysteriously: post-1970|List of people who disappeared]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book|last=Cesarani|first=David|authorlink=David Cesarani|title=Eichmann: His Life and Crimes|publisher=Vintage|location=London, UK|year=2005|origyear=2004|isbn=978-0-09-944844-0|ref=harv}}\n\n{{Holocaust France}}\n{{Holocaust Slovakia}}\n{{Nazis South America|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brunner, Alois}}\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:2001 deaths]]\n[[Category:1980s missing person cases]]\n[[Category:Antisemitism in Austria]]\n[[Category:Antisemitism in Syria]]\n[[Category:Austrian expatriates in Syria]]\n[[Category:Austrian Nazis]]\n[[Category:Austrian people convicted of crimes against humanity]]\n[[Category:Austrian people of Hungarian descent]]\n[[Category:Drancy internment camp]]\n[[Category:Fugitives wanted on crimes against humanity charges]]\n[[Category:Fugitives wanted on war crimes charges]]\n[[Category:Gestapo personnel]]\n[[Category:Holocaust perpetrators in Austria]]\n[[Category:Holocaust perpetrators in France]]\n[[Category:Holocaust perpetrators in Greece]]\n[[Category:Holocaust perpetrators in Slovakia]]\n[[Category:Hungarian-German people]]\n[[Category:Missing people]]\n[[Category:Nazi concentration camp commandants]]\n[[Category:Nazi fugitives]]\n[[Category:Nazi leaders]]\n[[Category:Nazis sentenced to death in absentia]]\n[[Category:People from Jennersdorf District]]\n[[Category:RSHA personnel]]\n[[Category:SS-Hauptsturmf\u00fchrer]]\n[[Category:The Holocaust in Thessaloniki]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n|name= Alois Brunner\n|image= Alois Brunner.JPG\n|caption= Brunner in 1940\n|birth_date= {{birth date|1912|4|8|df=y}}\n|death_date= {{death year and age|2001|1912}}\n|birth_place= [[Rohrbrunn|N\u00e1dk\u00fat]], [[Kingdom of Hungary]], [[Austria-Hungary]] \n|death_place= [[Damascus]], [[Syria]]\n|placeofburial= Al-Affif cemetery, Damascus, Syria (likely)\n|allegiance={{flag|Nazi Germany}}\n|branch=[[File:Schutzstaffel Abzeichen.svg|20px]] [[Schutzstaffel]]\n|serviceyears=1932\u20131945\n|rank= [[Hauptsturmf\u00fchrer]] (head storm leader)\n|battles  = [[World War II]]\n|commands= [[Drancy internment camp]]\n|laterwork= Advisor to the [[Syria]]n government; arms dealer in [[Egypt]]\n}}\n\n'''Alois Brunner''' (8 April 1912 \u2013 2001<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/nazi-war-criminal-alois-brunner-died-syria-basement-061723415.html|title=Nazi war criminal Brunner 'died in Syria basement in 2001'|website=Yahoo!|access-date=24 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"timesofisrael\"/>) was an Austrian ''[[Schutzstaffel]]'' (SS) officer who worked as [[Adolf Eichmann]]'s assistant. Brunner is held responsible for sending over 100,000 [[European Jews]] to ghettos and concentration camps in eastern Europe. He was commander of the [[Drancy internment camp]] outside Paris from June 1943 to August 1944, from which nearly 24,000 people were deported.\n\nAfter some narrow escapes from the [[Allies of World War II|Allies]] in the immediate aftermath of [[World War II]], Brunner fled West Germany in 1954, first for Egypt, then Syria, where he remained until his death. He was the object of many manhunts and investigations over the years by different groups, including the [[Simon Wiesenthal Center]], the [[Serge and Beate Klarsfeld|Klarsfelds]] and others. He was condemned to death ''[[trial in absentia|in absentia]]'' in France in 1954 for [[crimes against humanity]]. He lost an eye and then the fingers of his left hand as a result of [[letter bomb]]s sent to him in 1961 and 1980, reportedly by Israeli [[Secret service|intelligence]].<ref name=\"Bergman\" /> The government of Syria under [[Hafez el-Assad]] came close to [[extradition|extraditing]] him to [[East Germany]] before this plan was halted by the [[fall of the Berlin Wall]] in November 1989. Brunner survived all the attempts to detain him and was unrepentant about his activities to the end. During his long residence in Syria, Brunner was reportedly granted [[Right of asylum|asylum]], a generous salary and protection by the ruling [[Ba'ath Party]] in exchange for his advice on effective [[torture]] and [[interrogation technique]]s used by the Germans in [[World War II]].<ref>Adam Chandler, [https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2014/12/eichmanns-best-man-lived-and-died-in-syria/383296 \"Eichmann's Best Man Lived and Died in Syria\"], ''The Atlantic Magazine'', 1 December 2014.</ref>\n\nStarting in the 1990s and continuing for two decades, there was periodic media speculation about Brunner's exact whereabouts and his possible demise. In November 2014, the [[Simon Wiesenthal Center]] reported that Brunner had died in Syria in 2010,<ref name=swc2014/> and that he was buried somewhere in Damascus. The exact date of death and place of death are unknown, with recent information pointing to 2001 as the year of his death.\n\n==Second World War==\nBorn in [[Rohrbrunn|N\u00e1dk\u00fat]], [[Vas County (former)|Vas, Austria-Hungary]] (now Rohrbrunn, [[Burgenland]], Austria), he was the son of Joseph Brunner and Ann Kruise. He joined the [[Nazi Party]] in 1931 and the ''[[Sturmabteilung]]'' (SA) in 1932. After joining the SS in 1938, he was assigned to the staff of the [[Central Office for Jewish Emigration]] in Austria and became its director in 1939. He worked closely with [[Adolf Eichmann]] on the [[Nisko Plan]], a failed attempt to set up a Jewish reservation in [[Nisko|Nisko, Poland]], later that same year.{{sfn|Cesarani|2005|p=128}}\n\nBrunner held the rank of SS-''[[Hauptsturmf\u00fchrer]]'' (captain) when he organized deportations to [[Nazi concentration camps]] from [[Vichy France]] and [[Slovak Republic (1939-1945)|Slovakia]]. He was commander of a train of Jews deported from [[Vienna]] to [[Riga]] in February 1942. En route, Brunner shot and killed Jewish financier Siegmund Bosel, who, although ill, had been hauled out of a Vienna hospital and placed on the train. According to historian Gertrude Schneider, who as a young girl was deported to Riga on the same train, but survived the Holocaust:{{quote|Alois Brunner chained Bosel, still in his pajamas, to the platform of the first car\u2014our car\u2014and berated him for having been a profiteer. The old man repeatedly asked for mercy; he was very ill, and it was bitterly cold. Finally Brunner wearied of the game and shot him. Afterward, he walked into the car and asked whether anyone had heard anything. After being assured that no one had, he seemed satisfied and left.<ref>Schneider, Gertrude, ''Journey Into Terror: The Story of the Riga Ghetto'', p. 25, Westport, Connecticut, USA, Praeger, 2001; {{ISBN|0-275-97050-7}}</ref>}}\n\nBefore being named commander of [[Drancy internment camp]] near Paris in June 1943, Brunner deported 43,000 Jews from [[Vienna]] and 46,000 from [[Salonika]].<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite news|title=French court strikes blow against fugitive Nazi|url=https://www.theguardian.com/nazis/article/0,2763,445717,00.html|publisher=The Guardian|date=3 March 2003|accessdate=30 July 2007|location=London, UK|first=Jon|last=Henley}}</ref> He was personally sent by Eichmann in 1944 to [[Slovak Republic (1939-1945)|Slovakia]] to oversee the deportation of Jews. In the last days of the [[Third Reich]], he managed to deport another 13,500 from Slovakia<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> to [[Theresienstadt]], [[Sachsenhausen concentration camp|Sachsenhausen]], [[Bergen-Belsen concentration camp|Bergen-Belsen]], and [[Stutthof]] of whom a few survived; the remainder, including all the children, were sent to Auschwitz, where none are known to have survived.<ref name=\"Porter-2009\">{{cite book|last=Porter|first=Anna|authorlink=Anna Porter|title=Kasztner's Train: The True Story of an Unknown Hero of the Holocaust|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pfY4gV1B6moC&pg=PA246|accessdate=11 January 2016|date=26 May 2009|publisher=Walker Publishing|location=New York|isbn=978-0-8027-1596-8|page=[https://archive.org/details/kasztnerstrain00anna/page/246 246]|chapter=23. The End of Summer|origyear=2007|oclc=236340976|quote=In mid-October, Captain Alois Brunner began to empty the Sered camp of its almost twenty thousand Slovak Jews, even as the Slovak insurrection was defeated by four German SS divisions. Some of those who were sent to Theresienstadt survived the war. A few survived at the Sachsenhausen camp in Germany, Stutthof in Poland, and Bergen-Belsen. The rest, including all the children, were murdered in Auschwitz. Brunner had always taken great pleasure in the murder of children.|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/kasztnerstrain00anna/page/246}}</ref> According to some accounts, Brunner was responsible for the deportation of 129,000 people to death camps.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=FELSTINER|first=MARY|title=Commandant of Drancy: Alois Brunner and the Jews of France|date=1987|journal=Holocaust and Genocide Studies|volume=2|issue=1|pages=21\u201347|doi=10.1093/hgs/2.1.21|issn=8756-6583}}</ref>\n\nWhile serving as the commandant at Drancy, Brunner was remembered for his exceptional brutality. He personally conducted interrogations of new prisoners, and survivors of the camp have claimed that his office was covered in bloodstains and bullet holes. He instituted torture even for slight offences. As he was personally responsible to Eichmann, he circumvented the typical chain of command that included [[Helmut Knochen]], the Chief of the SS in Paris, and [[Heinz R\u00f6thke|Heinz Rothke]], the Jewish Affairs expert of the German police. He introduced a rigid system of categorization to control the inmates using information about their race and ethnicity derived from the interrogations. He deliberately misled prisoners about the living standards of their destinations at the extermination camps in the [[General Government]], including [[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz-Birkenau]]. Brunner also led round-ups of Jews in the [[Italian occupation of France|Italian Military Administration of France]] when the Germans assumed control in 1943 following the [[Armistice of Cassibile]], ended all legal exemptions preventing Jews from being deported by Vichy France, and extended the deportations to Jews of French nationality. He continued deportations and arrests even as the [[Allies of World War II|Allies]] and the [[Free France|Free French Forces]] advanced towards Paris.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Postwar flight and escape to Syria==\nIn an 1985 interview with the West German magazine ''[[Bunte]]'', Brunner described how he escaped capture by the Allies immediately after World War II. The identity of Brunner was apparently mixed up with that of another SS member with the same surname, Anton Brunner, who was executed for war crimes. Alois, like [[Josef Mengele]], did not have the [[SS blood group tattoo|SS blood type tattoo]], which prevented his identity from detection in an Allied prison camp. Anton Brunner, who had worked in [[Vienna]] deporting Jews, was confused after the war with Alois due to the shared surname, including by historians such as [[Gerald Reitlinger]].<ref>Schneider, Gertrude, ''Journey into terror: story of the Riga Ghetto'' (2nd abbr. edition), Westport, Connecticut, Praeger, 2001, pp. 54, 167; {{ISBN|0-275-97050-7}}</ref>\n\nClaiming he had \"received official documents under a false name from American authorities\", Brunner claimed he had found work as a driver for the [[United States Army]] in the period after the war.<ref>{{cite news|title=In Syria, a Long-Hunted Nazi Talks|newspaper=The New York Times|date=29 October 1985|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/10/29/world/in-syria-a-long-hunted-nazi-talks.html|first=James M.|last=Markham}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Nazi Criminal Says Mixup Aided His Escape|newspaper=The New York Times|date=7 November 1985|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/11/07/world/around-the-world-nazi-criminal-says-mixup-aided-his-escape.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=George J. Annas|title=Mengele's Birthmark: The Nuremberg Code in United States Courts|year=1991|journal=The Journal of Contemporary Health Law and Policy|volume=7|pages=17\u201346|pmid=11645690}}</ref>\n\nIt has been alleged that Brunner found a working relationship after World War II with the ''[[Gehlen Organization]]''.<ref>{{cite book|author=Peter Wyden|title=The Hitler Virus: The Insidious Legacy of Adolf Hitler|year=2001|publisher=Arcade Publishing}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first1=Georg|last1=Hafner|first2=Esther|last2=Schapira|title=Die Akte Alois Brunner|language=de|year=2000|publisher=Campus Verlag}}</ref><ref name=\"Ibtimes.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/alois-brunner-nazi-war-criminal-who-found-home-syria-725811|title=Alois Brunner: The Nazi War Criminal Who Found a Home in Syria|publisher=Ibtimes.com|date=18 July 2012|accessdate=4 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe fled [[West Germany]] only in 1954, on a fake [[Red Cross]] passport, first to Rome, then [[Republic of Egypt (1953\u20131958)|Egypt]], where he worked as a weapons dealer, and then to [[Syrian Republic (1946\u201363)|Syria]], where he took the [[pseudonym]] of Dr. Georg Fischer. In Syria, he was hired as a government adviser. The exact nature of his work is unknown. Syria had long refused entry to French investigators as well as to [[Nazi hunter]] [[Serge Klarsfeld]], who spent nearly 15 years bringing the case to court in France. [[Simon Wiesenthal]] tried unsuccessfully to trace Brunner's whereabouts. However, [[communism|communist]] [[East Germany]], led by [[Erich Honecker]], negotiated with Syria in the late 1980s to have Brunner [[extradition|extradited]] and arrested in Berlin.<ref name=\"halted-extradition\">{{cite web|url=http://www.expatica.com/de/news/german-news/fall-of-berlin-wall-halted-extradition-of-key-nazi-report_166452.html|title=Fall of Berlin Wall halted extradition of key Nazi: report|publisher=Expatica.com|accessdate=9 November 2012|date=2009-10-24}}</ref> The government of Syria under [[Hafez el-Assad]] was close to extraditing Brunner to East Germany, but the [[fall of the Berlin Wall]] in November 1989 severed contacts between the two regimes and halted the extradition plan.<ref name=\"halted-extradition\"/>\n \t\nIn the ''[[Bunte]]'' interview, Brunner was quoted as saying he regrets nothing and that all of the Jews deserved their fate. According to a widely quoted 1987 telephone interview with the ''[[Chicago Sun Times]]'', he was reported to have said: \"All of [the Jews] deserved to die because they were the Devil's agents and human garbage. I have no regrets and would do it again.\"<ref name=\"US State Dept document\">{{cite web|last1=US Department of State|title=Nazi War Criminal Alois Brunner's Presence in Damascus Hits the Papers Again|url=http://nsarchive.gwu.edu/NSAEBB/NSAEBB150/box14_di_file/doc04.pdf|website=The National Security Archive|accessdate=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nUntil the early 1990s, he lived in an apartment building on 7 Rue Haddad in Damascus, meeting with foreigners and occasionally being photographed.<ref name=\"guardian2001\">{{cite news|author=Jon Henley in Paris|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2001/mar/03/warcrimes.germany|title=French court strikes blow against fugitive Nazi|publisher=The Guardian|date=3 March 2001|accessdate=4 March 2014|location=London, UK}}</ref> In the 1990s, the French Embassy received reports that Brunner was meeting regularly and having tea with former East German nationals.<ref>{{cite web|author=Georges Malbrunot|date=21 July 2011|url=http://blog.lefigaro.fr/malbrunot/2011/07/alois-brunner-les-allemands-on.html|title=Alo\u00efs Brunner: les Allemands ont d\u00e9truit les notes de renseignements|publisher=Blog.lefigaro.fr|accessdate=4 March 2014}}</ref> According to ''[[The Guardian]]'', he was last seen alive by reliable witnesses in 1992.<ref name=\"guardian2001\"/>\n\nIn December 1999, unconfirmed reports surfaced that Brunner had died in 1996 and been buried in a Damascus cemetery. However, he was reportedly sighted at the Meridian Hotel in [[Damascus]] by German journalists that same year, where he was said to be living under police protection.<ref>{{cite news|author=Jo Glanville|url=https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/1999/nov/28/featuresreview.review|title=He's the last Nazi criminal still at large. But where is he?|publisher=Guardian|date=28 November 1999|accessdate=4 March 2014|location=London, UK}}</ref> The last reported sighting of him was at the Meridian Hotel in late 2001 by German journalists.<ref name=\"Ibtimes.com\"/>\n\nIn 2011, ''[[Der Spiegel]]'' reported that the German intelligence service [[Bundesnachrichtendienst]] had destroyed its file on Brunner in the 1990s, and that remarks in remaining files contain conflicting statements as to whether Brunner had worked for the BND at some point.<ref>{{cite news|title=BND vernichtete Akten zu SS-Verbrecher Brunner|language=de|publisher=[[Der Spiegel]]|date=20 July 2001}}</ref>\n\n==Assassination attempts==\nIn 1961 and 1980, letter bombs were sent to Brunner while he was a resident in Syria. As a result of the letter bomb he received in 1961, he lost an eye, and in 1980, he lost the fingers on his left hand when the parcel blew up in his hands. The senders of the letter bombs were not known.<ref>[http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,960365,00.html \"The Nazi of Damascus\"], ''Time Magazine'', 11 November 1985.</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">''{{lang|fr|Alois Brunner \u2013 La haine irr\u00e9ductible}}'', by Didier Epelbaum, preface by [[Serge Klarsfeld]], published by Calmann-L\u00e9vy, January 1990.</ref>\n\nA 2018 article in ''[[Newsweek]]'' by journalist [[Ronen Bergman]] disclosed that the 1961 bomb was sent by Military Intelligence Unit 188, a branch of the [[Israel Defense Forces]] and was the first target of a new method of [[letter bomb]] that was developed for deployment against ex-Nazi scientists working for [[Gamal Abdel Nasser]] in developing missiles targeting Israel. The article, excerpted from Bergman's book ''[[Rise and Kill First]]'', says that Brunner was located by Israeli spy [[Eli Cohen]].<ref name=\"Bergman\">{{cite news|last1=Bergman|first1=Ronen|authorlink1=Ronen Bergman|title=Israel's secret war against Hitler's scientists|url=http://www.newsweek.com/2018/04/20/israel-secret-war-mossad-hitler-scientists-world-war-ii-egypt-nasser-883630.html|accessdate=25 May 2018|work=Newsweek|date=12 April 2018|language=en}}</ref> According to information released by the Israeli intelligence agency [[Mossad]], it was behind the 1980 bomb.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/.premium-the-mossads-botched-assassination-attempts-on-nazi-war-criminals-1.5449633 | title=Not Just Mengele the Mossad's Botched Assassination Attempts on Nazi War Criminals| newspaper=Haaretz| date=2017-09-11| last1=Aderet| first1=Ofer}}</ref>\n\n==Convictions in absentia==\nGermany and other countries unsuccessfully requested his extradition. He was twice sentenced to death ''[[trial in absentia|in absentia]]'' in the 1950s; one of those convictions was in France in 1954. In August 1987, an [[Interpol]] \"[[red notice]]\" was issued for him. In 1995, German state prosecutors in [[Cologne]] and [[Frankfurt]] posted a $330,000 reward for information leading to his arrest.<ref name=\"McKale\">Donald M. McKale, {{cite book|title=Nazis after Hitler: How Perpetrators of the Holocaust Cheated Justice and Truth|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers|year=2011|isbn=978-1442213180|page=290|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=paOLRR7q15wC&lpg=PP1&pg=PP1}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 March 2001, he was found guilty ''in absentia'' by a French court for [[crimes against humanity]],<ref name=\"about\">Bridget Johnson,[http://worldnews.about.com/od/crime/tp/nazimostwanted.htm \"Most Wanted Nazis\"], About.com; accessed 27 December 2016.</ref> including the arrest and deportation of 345 orphans from the [[Paris]] region (which had not been judged in the earlier trials) and was sentenced to [[life imprisonment]]. According to [[Serge Klarsfeld]], the trial was largely symbolic\u2014an effort to honour the memories of victims. Klarsfeld's own father, arrested in 1943, was reportedly one of Brunner's victims.<ref name=\"Guardian2001\">[https://www.theguardian.com/nazis/article/0,2763,445717,00.html \"French court strikes blow against fugitive Nazi\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 3 March 2001.</ref>\n\n==Later attempts to locate==\nIn 2003, British newspaper ''[[The Guardian]]'' described him as \"the world's highest-ranking Nazi fugitive believed still alive.\" Brunner was last reported to be living in 2001 in [[Syria]], whose government had long rebuffed international efforts to locate or apprehend him, but was presumed dead {{as of|2012|lc=y}}.<ref name=euronews>{{cite news|title=Who are the most wanted Nazis?|url=http://www.euronews.com/2012/07/16/who-are-the-most-wanted-nazis|accessdate=24 July 2014|work=Euronews|date=16 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, for an episode titled \"Hunting Nazis\", the television series ''[[Unsolved History]]'' used [[facial recognition software]] to compare Alois Brunner's official SS photograph with a recent photo of \"Georg Fischer\", and came up with a match of 8.1 points out of 10, which they claimed was, despite the elapse of over 50 years in aging, equivalent to a match with 95% certainty. [[Brazilians|Brazilian]] police were reportedly investigating whether a suspect living in the country under an assumed name is actually Alois Brunner. Deputy Commander Asher Ben-Artzi, the head of Israel's [[Interpol]] and Foreign Liaison Section, passed on a Brazilian request for Brunner's [[fingerprint]]s to Nazi hunter [[Efraim Zuroff]], head of the [[Simon Wiesenthal Center]] in [[Jerusalem]], but Zuroff could not find any.<ref>[http://www.jpost.com/Jewish-World/Jewish-News/Intl-hunt-on-for-top-Nazi-fugitive \"Int'l hunt on for top Nazi fugitive\"], ''[[The Jerusalem Post]]'', 28 December 2005.</ref>\n\nIn July 2007, the Austrian Justice Ministry declared that they would pay \u20ac50,000 for information leading to his arrest and extradition to Austria.<ref>[http://www.justiz.gv.at/_cms_upload/_docs/auslobung_englisch.pdf Warrant of Apprehension], ''Austrian Justice Ministry''; accessed 27 December 2016.{{in lang|de}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2009, the Simon Wiesenthal Center acknowledged the \"slim\" possibility of Brunner still being alive.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/in_depth/7857753.stm|title=The hunt for the last Nazis|date=23 March 2009|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref> In 2011, some media reports still insisted he could be alive.<ref>{{cite news|first=Ben|last=Forer|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/worlds-wanted-left-list/story?id=13693016|title=World's Most Wanted: Who's Left on the List?|work=[[ABC News]]|date=26 May 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.20min.ch/news/dossier/denhaag/story/Die-meistgesuchten-Kriegsverbrecher-24050426|title=Die meistgesuchten Kriegsverbrecher|work=20 Minuten|date=26 May 2011|accessdate=10 June 2011|language=German}}</ref>\n\nBrunner was removed from the Simon Wiesenthal Center's [[List of most-wanted Nazi war criminals]] in 2014.<ref name=swc2014/>\n\n==Death==\nOn 30 November 2014, the [[Simon Wiesenthal Center]] reported receiving credible information that Brunner had died in [[Syria]] in 2001. He would have been 97 or 98 years old. Partly due to the ongoing [[Syrian Civil War]], the exact date and place of death are unknown.<ref name=swc2014>{{cite book|publisher=[[Simon Wiesenthal Center]]|location=Los Angeles, California|title=2014 Annual Report on the Status of Nazi War Criminals|url=http://www.wiesenthal.com/atf/cf/%7B54d385e6-f1b9-4e9f-8e94-890c3e6dd277%7D/WIESENTHAL-CENTER_2014-ANNUAL-NAZI-WAR-CRIMNAL-REPORT-V.2.PDF|year=2014|access-date=2014-06-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181030024822/http://www.wiesenthal.com/atf/cf/%7B54d385e6-f1b9-4e9f-8e94-890c3e6dd277%7D/WIESENTHAL-CENTER_2014-ANNUAL-NAZI-WAR-CRIMNAL-REPORT-V.2.PDF|archive-date=2018-10-30|url-status = dead|df=}}</ref><ref name=\"time.com\">\"A Notorious Nazi War Criminal Died in Syria Four Years Ago\", time.com, 2 December 2014.</ref>\n\nAccording to the director of the Wiesenthal Center, Dr. [[Efraim Zuroff]], the information came from a \"reliable\" former German [[secret service]] agent who had served in the Middle East. The information also was reported in the press. The new evidence revealed that Brunner was buried in an unknown location in Damascus around 2010, unrepentant of his crimes to the end. Zuroff said that, owing to the civil war in Syria, the exact location of Brunner's grave is impossible to know.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-30275358|title=Nazi war criminal Alois Brunner 'died in Syria'|work=BBC|date=1 December 2014|accessdate=27 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, a French magazine ''{{ill|XXI (magazine)|lt=XXI|fr|XXI}}'' interviewed one of Brunner's guards in Syria as he was locked up in a squalid Damascus basement at the end of the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.revue21.fr/tous_les_numeros#n-37_le-nazi-de-damas|title=Le nazi de Damas|website=Revue XXI|language=French|date=11 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-38586945|title=Nazi war criminal Alois Brunner 'died in Syria squalor'|website=BBC|date=11 January 2017}}</ref> The guard said that Brunner \"suffered and cried a lot in his final years, everyone heard him\", \"couldn\u2019t even wash\" and had to eat \"an egg or a potato\". He also added that Brunner died in December 2001 and was buried at Al-Affif cemetery in Damascus.<ref name=\"timesofisrael\">{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/nazi-war-criminal-alois-brunner-died-in-syria-basement-in-2001-report/|title=Nazi war criminal Alois Brunner died in Syria basement in 2001 \u2013 report|website=The Times of Isreal|date=11 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of people who disappeared mysteriously: post-1970|List of people who disappeared]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book|last=Cesarani|first=David|authorlink=David Cesarani|title=Eichmann: His Life and Crimes|publisher=Vintage|location=London, UK|year=2005|origyear=2004|isbn=978-0-09-944844-0|ref=harv}}\n\n{{Holocaust France}}\n{{Holocaust Slovakia}}\n{{Nazis South America|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brunner, Alois}}\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:2001 deaths]]\n[[Category:1980s missing person cases]]\n[[Category:Antisemitism in Austria]]\n[[Category:Antisemitism in Syria]]\n[[Category:Austrian expatriates in Syria]]\n[[Category:Austrian Nazis]]\n[[Category:Austrian people convicted of crimes against humanity]]\n[[Category:Austrian people of Hungarian descent]]\n[[Category:Drancy internment camp]]\n[[Category:Fugitives wanted on crimes against humanity charges]]\n[[Category:Fugitives wanted on war crimes charges]]\n[[Category:Gestapo personnel]]\n[[Category:Holocaust perpetrators in Austria]]\n[[Category:Holocaust perpetrators in France]]\n[[Category:Holocaust perpetrators in Greece]]\n[[Category:Holocaust perpetrators in Slovakia]]\n[[Category:Hungarian-German people]]\n[[Category:Missing people]]\n[[Category:Nazi concentration camp commandants]]\n[[Category:Nazi fugitives]]\n[[Category:Nazi leaders]]\n[[Category:Nazis sentenced to death in absentia]]\n[[Category:People from Jennersdorf District]]\n[[Category:RSHA personnel]]\n[[Category:SS-Hauptsturmf\u00fchrer]]\n[[Category:The Holocaust in Thessaloniki]]\n", "name_user": "PohranicniStraze", "label": "safe", "comment": "sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alois_Brunner"}
